The inkscaper package: R wrapper for Inkscape

2023-09-13

The inkscaper package provide a modern and simple toolkit for Scalable Vector Graphics (SVG) processing in R. It wraps the Inkscape which is a Free and open source vector graphics editor for GNU/Linux, Windows and macOS.

It offers a rich set of features and is widely used for both artistic and technical illustrations such as cartoons, clip art, logos, typography, diagramming and flowcharting. It uses vector graphics to allow for sharp printouts and renderings at unlimited resolution and is not bound to a fixed number of pixels like raster graphics. Inkscape uses the standardized SVG file format as its main format, which is supported by many other applications including web browsers.

Installing inkscape

To install Inkscape on your platform follow the instruction available at: https://inkscape.org/

Note: during Windows installation allow set path

Using Inkscape Actions

While obviously Inkscape is primarily intended as a GUI application, it can be used for doing SVG processing on the command line as well. Inkscape Actions available in versions Inkscape 1.3 (0e150ed6c4, 2023-07-21) are listed below.

Function inx_actions()

In this example we download a SVG file from repository, convert it to PNG and plot it in R.

library(inkscaper)
output = "https://dev.w3.org/SVG/tools/svgweb/samples/svg-files/cartman.svg" %>% 
  inx_actions(actions = NA, ext = ".png")

This is PNG generated with this procedure:

Using Inkscape Extensions

Inkscape Extensions are small programs that extend Inkscapes functionality. They can provide features for specific tasks, experimentation, or art styles. They can also add support for special hardware or different export formats. While many extensions are included with Inkscape, you can also install extensions written by third parties or write your own. The table below shows the list of extensions available in Inkscape of version Inkscape 1.3 (0e150ed6c4, 2023-07-21) with descriptions.

Function inx_extension()

In this example we download SVG, convert it to DXF and read with sf package. Simple features (LINESTRING) are plotted with ggplot2.

Heart

In this example we define SF linestrings from points given by a formula for Heart Curve and convert it into SVG path.

heart <- tibble(t = seq(0, 2*pi, 0.1)) %>%
  mutate( x = 16*sin(t)^3 ) %>%
  mutate( y = 13*cos(t)-5*cos(2*t)-2*cos(3*t)-cos(4*t))

heart <- heart %>% bind_rows(heart %>% slice(1)) %>% select(x, y) %>% as.matrix() %>%
  st_linestring() %>% st_sfc() %>% st_sf()
heart %>% ggplot() +
  geom_sf()

output = heart %>% inx_sf2svg() 
## writing: substituting ENGCRS["Undefined Cartesian SRS with unknown unit"] for missing CRS

Actions on Simple Features

sf_1 = matrix(c(0,0,10,0,10,10,0,10,0,0),ncol=2, byrow=TRUE)  %>%
  list() %>% st_multilinestring() %>% st_sfc() %>% st_sf()
sf_2 = matrix(c(1,1,1,2,2,2,2,1,1,1),ncol=2, byrow=TRUE) %>%
  list() %>% st_multilinestring() %>% st_sfc() %>% st_sf()
collection <- sf_1 %>% bind_rows(sf_2)
collection %>% ggplot() +
  geom_sf()

inx_svg = collection %>% inx_sf2svg()

R Logo

logo = system.file("extdata", "R_logo.svg", package = "inkscaper") %>%
  inx_svg2sf() %>% 
  select(geometry)
## Reading layer `entities' from data source 
##   `C:\Users\jacek\AppData\Local\Temp\Rtmp8sDamw\inx_30cc5c3e4d8d.dxf' 
##   using driver `DXF'
## Simple feature collection with 301 features and 6 fields
## Geometry type: LINESTRING
## Dimension:     XY
## Bounding box:  xmin: 0.239712 ymin: 0.512699 xmax: 191.0289 ymax: 147.6373
## CRS:           NA
# POLYGON: ellipse
ellipse <- logo %>% slice(1:128) %>%
  select(geometry) %>% st_union() %>% st_polygonize() %>%
  first() %>%
  first() %>% st_sfc()  %>% st_sf(geometry = .)
hole <- logo %>% slice(129:215) %>%
  select(geometry) %>% st_union() %>% st_polygonize() %>%
  first() %>%
  first() %>% st_sfc()  %>% st_sf(geometry = .)
ellipse <- ellipse %>% st_difference(hole) %>% mutate(colour = "#b8b8bdff")

# POLYGON: R letter
rletter <- logo %>% slice(216:276) %>%
  select(geometry) %>% st_union() %>% st_polygonize() %>%
  first() %>%
  first() %>% st_sfc() %>% st_sf(geometry = .)
hole <- logo %>% slice(277:301)  %>%
  select(geometry) %>% st_union() %>% st_polygonize() %>%
  first() %>%
  first() %>% st_sfc()  %>% st_sf(geometry = .)
rletter <- rletter %>% st_difference(hole) %>% mutate(colour = "#1c61b3ff")

ggplot() +
  geom_sf(data = ellipse, aes(fill = colour)) +
  geom_sf(data = rletter, aes(fill = colour)) +
  scale_fill_identity()

Inkscape Logo

output = system.file("extdata", "Inkscape_logo.svg", package = "inkscaper") %>%
  inx_svg2sf() %>% 
  select(geometry) %>% st_union() %>% st_polygonize() %>% first()

  st_union(output %>% nth(4)) 
output %>%
  ggplot() + 
  aes(fill = "black") +
  geom_sf() +
  scale_fill_identity()

Non-GUI environments

Some known limitations:

  • in a non-GUI environment such as Colab, some actions will not work because they require a GUI to run, although the inkscaper package only requires the CLI to run commands.

======= - Only actions that dont require a desktop may be used.
